# Project Architecture

This project is a Vue.js SPA frontend talking to a FastAPI backend, which persists data in MongoDB.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  userBrowser["UserBrowser"] --> vueApp["VueApp (SPA)"]
  vueApp --> fastApi["FastAPIBackend"]
  fastApi --> mongoDb["MongoDB"]
```

# Folder Layout

- `frontend/`: Vue application (components, views, routes, state, and UI utilities).
- `backend/`: FastAPI application (routers, services, schemas, and config).
- `infra/` (optional): Deployment, Docker, and environment configuration.

# Boundaries & Responsibilities

- Vue components handle UI, local state, and calling typed HTTP APIs; they do not contain business or persistence logic.
- FastAPI routers focus on request/response wiring and delegate logic to services.
- Services (or use-case modules) implement business rules and call MongoDB through a dedicated data-access layer.
- MongoDB access is centralized (e.g., repositories/DAOs), not called directly from routers or Vue code.

# Minimal Conventions

- Prefer feature folders within `frontend/` and `backend/` when a domain grows (e.g., `frontend/features/dashboard`, `backend/features/dashboard`).
- Name Vue components in `PascalCase` (`DashboardPanel.vue`) and FastAPI modules in `snake_case` (`dashboard_routes.py`).
- Add new endpoints under the appropriate router module and expose them via a small API client module in `frontend/`.
- Keep cross-cutting utilities in clearly named `shared` or `common` subfolders rather than mixing them into feature folders.
